Challenge To H.M.O.'s Maternity Limits
nytimes_articles.abstract:
WHEN Allison Bissar had her first child 18 months ago, she was determined not to enter the hospital before midnight. 

     " 'I'd been in labor all day," she said, "and the contractions were so bad I  was gritting my teeth." But she knew that her health-insurance company, U.S. Healthcare, covered just 24 hours of maternity care, and gambled that she would  have a few extra hours in Mercy Hospital if she could hold out. She was admitted shortly after midnight, and her baby was born at 7:08 A.M.

SOAPBOX;The One We'll Talk About
nytimes_articles.abstract:
I WASN'T alive for the blizzard of 1947, but my parents, newly married and living in Elizabeth, would refer to it whenever there was a heavy snow. "This is nothing compared to the blizzard of 1947," they always said. My siblings and I felt we had missed something wonderful. Would our snows ever equal theirs? 

     Early Sunday morning I sensed that the impending storm would be special. Neighbors kept returning to Farragut Place with their cars laden with groceries. My husband set forth for the supermarket and returned four hours later with enough food to withstand a month's siege and with a tale of having heroically endured a line at the cash register in the local Shop Rite that snaked around the entire inside of the store.

Conquerors and Colonists
nytimes_articles.abstract: THE RISE AND FALL OF THE BRITISH EMPIRE By Lawrence James. Illustrated. 704 pp. New York: St. Martin's Press. $35.    BRITAIN'S imperial history has always attracted authors. Some are struck by its entertainment value, excitement, ceremonies, grand chronological sweep and infinite global variety. Others dwell on its tragedies and atrocities, not least the extermination of indigenous peoples, its association with slavery, or its appropriation of raw materials and the impetus given to environmental damage. The processes of empire building and demolition offer something to interest everyone. The same can be said of Lawrence James's epic account, "The Rise and Fall of the British Empire," the latest in a line including volumes by Angus Calder and Jan Morris.

(Ages 8 to 12)    LIBRARIANS and critics have been speaking ill of series books for children since the turn of the century, when the Stratemeyer Literary Syndicate began spewing out its endless adventures of the Rover Boys and Tom Swift, all distinguished by a faithful adherence to formula, shallow characterization and reader-comforting predictability. FILM VIEW;Why Reality Will Never Compute
nytimes_articles.abstract:
IN A RECENT ARTICLE IN THE NEW YORK TIMES about the technological changes overtaking the movie business, the director George Lucas weighed in heavily in favor of digital film making. Computers, he said, make shooting films on location obsolete. Furthermore, "there's no esthetic advantage whatsoever" in shooting on location, he said. "The issue is economics." 

     It's very hard to disagree with George Lucas. For one thing, he is a brilliant movie maker. For another, he has been responsible for some of the greatest technological advances ever in movies. Lucas has done extraordinary work on everything from sound quality and projection in theaters to the creation of breathtaking films. I can see why he has arrived at his notion that technology can replace location. He is really interested in creating myth, and for that task, reality gets in the way. There is no use for it.

NEIGHBORHOOD REPORT: SUNSET PARK;Cold Days for Finnish Society
nytimes_articles.abstract:
Imatra Hall, a two-story, mustard-colored clapboard house on 40th Street in Sunset Park, once flowed with immigrants from Finland. Patrons from the surrounding area, once known as Finntown, crowded the dark wood bar, the dance floor and the downstairs sauna and in the summer enjoyed the barbecue and beach  chairs on the front lawn. 

     Today, with most of the Finnish community long since gone to places like Florida and Long Island, the hall is struggling to stay open. Even buying a Christmas tree for the hall's front lawn was difficult -- the 104-year-old Finnish Aid Society, the club of Finnish-Americans that owns the hall, had to split the $65 cost with a group that rents space in the building.

ON THE MAP;Sports, and Buddies, for Disabled Children in Middletown
nytimes_articles.abstract:
The Lincroft Little League's Challenger Division, for children with mental and physical disablities, began in 1991. It was one of the first in the state, but it was only the beginning. 

     Under Paul J. Hooker, then president of the league, the division branched out into a program -- Challenged Youth Sports -- for disabled children throughout Middletown, the Monmouth County township that includes Lincroft. Now it includes basketball, tennis and soccer as well as baseball, and it has almost 300 participants: more than 100 children, 150 teen-age "buddies" -- volunteers who pair up with the children and help them play -- and 40 adult volunteers.

RESULTS PLUS
Siberia Belies Its Somber Image
nytimes_articles.abstract:
WHEN my friends in Moscow heard that I was going to Siberia in February, they said, "It's going to be cold." Actually, it was not that cold. Awaiting an Arctic blast as I stepped off the plane into the Siberian snow, I found myself feeling no more chilled than I would on a ski vacation. 

     Instead of the dark, frozen place of exile that I had expected -- home of the gulag and the salt mine -- I found streets filled with shoppers and vendors and  fur-hatted peasants carrying purchases home on mules. Shops were stocked with fresh fruit and stylish clothing, and crowded restaurants served hearty traditional fare like Siberian dumplings and stews. Residents, I learned, tend to flee not the cold, but the summer months, when temperatures soar to near 100  degrees and inchlong mosquitoes come out of hibernation. I had come to Siberia on business to study the economic life of the region, but during my 10-day stay  discovered much to enjoy. Siberia is surprisingly sunny in the winter months, when the deep colors of the forest shine against the snow.  The dark green taiga -- this is what the Siberians call their stunted pine forest -- is edged with the white of birch trees under a slate-blue sky. The huge Siberian land mass, bigger than the United States and Europe together, is mostly taiga. It runs 4,350 miles east of the Ural Mountains to the Pacific Ocean, unchanging, hardly  touched by humans.

TRAVEL ADVISORY;Buenos Aires Gets A Cultural Center
nytimes_articles.abstract:
The Centro Cultural Borges, housed in four wings of the 1889 Galerias Pacifico, opened in Buenos Aires in October. The building, which also houses an  upscale shopping mall, underwent extensive renovation. 

     By April, when it is fully operating, the center will occupy almost 100,000 square feet on three levels, and will feature performance spaces, a research center and workshops for artists. There will be an area devoted to the tango, with tango classes and the Hot-Tango Cafe, a coffee shop that features tango performances. About 40 percent of the center is open now, including two movie theaters, an auditorium, a coffee shop and several art galleries. The center is  financed by Argentine and international companies, including Telecom Argentina,  Moet & Chandon and Compaq Computer.

BOOKEND;Publishing and Other Near-Death Experiences
nytimes_articles.abstract:
Why can't book publishing be the way it is in books? Where are those heady nights on Beekman Place, those working days on lower Fifth, those underpaid trust-fun girls with the clacking Smith-coronas and the clicking low-heeled pumps from I. Miller? Where are Bennet Cerf's entrepreneurial seeds, Maxwell Perkins's worshipful authors, Mary McCarthy's well-red bedfellows? Where are the editorial assistants lunching frenetically at the Oyster Bar counter? Where are the pneumatic tubes running directly from Vassar and Smith to Viking and Scribners, sucking young English majors down their channels and depositing them  at chewed wooden desks with tins of lemon drops in the top drawers and manuscripts towering over the "in" boxes? Alas, lament entry levelers everywhere, the 30's are gone. So are the 40's, 50's, 60's and 70's for that matter. 

      There comes a time for every aspiring book publisher when she recognizes that her career, though inspired by Mary McCarthy's, will not resemble it. After a few weeks steeped in proposals for self-help books or unauthorized biographies of cable-access television stars, she realizes that there is no longer a May Day parade, a byline in The Nation is no longer immediately accessible to 22-year-old English majors, two-bedroom apartments on Jane Street are out of the single girl's price range, and Webster Hall is no longer filled with the literati but with drag queens. There comes a point when she notices that although she studied Homer, Austen and Melville, she will not be publishing them. There are a few holdouts from the "literary" camp, to be sure (the assistant may find herself remarking on the fact that here, in the world books,  "Literature" is considered a category as specific as "how to" or "occult"), but  there seem to be a disporortionate number of Oprah bios, guides to better sexual relationships and near-death-experience books, slugged for those on the inside as N.D.E. "A new N.D.E. title," screams the publisher, dollar signs glowing in her contact lenses. "Isn't this to die for?" To the publisher, N.D.E. means big  excitment and big bucks. To the assistant it can also stand for "not doing editing," "not drinking enough" or "nasty, despondent employee."

Books in Brief: NONFICTION;American Originals
nytimes_articles.abstract: Tired? Bored? Is the monotony of everyday life leaving you dead? HOLDING ON (Norton, $25), a collection of profiles of more than 50 American characters, will either cheerfully remind you that somewhere creative people pursue offbeat  passions or leave you annoyed that you are not among them. Take Robert Shields,  the author of the world's longest diary, a minute-by-minute account that comprises more than 34 million words; or Dewey Chafin, a snake handler in West Virginia who says, "Why I do it is because the Bible says to do it, and that's just the bottom line." Many of the people interviewed in "Holding On" are included not because of their personal peculiarities but because they are walking and (thankfully) talking bearers of history -- like Sylvia (Ray) Rivera, a drag queen, and Seymour Pine, a retired police officer, who faced off against  each other at the 1969 Stonewall riots; or Geneva Tisdale, a cook at the Woolworth's lunch counter in Greensboro, N.C., who recalls the student sit-ins there in 1960. The radio producer David Isay, who wrote the text, and Harvey Wang, who took the photographs, respect the distinctive lives they document in the book. As the novelist Henry Roth says in his foreword: "Exercising creativity helps us preserve one of our proudest, most noble, most precious possessions: dignity. As far as I'm concerned, dead, it doesn't matter whether we did or didn't preserve it. Comes to the same thing. . . . We're talking about being alive."   ALEXANDRA HALL

STYLE;A Historical Footnote
nytimes_articles.abstract:
For as long as the habit has existed, Frenchwomen have sneered at their American counterparts for mating street clothes with sneakers. To these stylish  Parisians, there is nothing more loathesome, more crass, more unspeakably tacky, than dressing to the nines from head to ankle and then slipping on a pair of Reeboks. Who cares about practicalities? Comfort? Mais non! As any Frenchwoman will tell you, it is the total look that counts, shoes included. 

     Yet, there they were, these same chic, sanctimonious Parisians, trotting down the grand boulevards last month in overcoats and les baskets. For the first few  days of the general strike, they insisted on wearing their patent-leather slingbacks and faux-alligator pumps, even if they were pounding the pavement for two hours to work and back. But eventually pain won out over style, and as one woman shuffling down the Avenue Bosquet in a pair of Nikes on a snowy morning put it, "I caved in."

A PARK OF HISTORY AND POETRY
nytimes_articles.abstract:
SEVENTY years ago, on Australia's Snowy Plain midway between Sydney and Melbourne, stood a lone weatherboard hut amid glowing spinifex grass and twisting gum trees. Davey Williamson spent his summers there along with his wife, children, some rabbits and a whole lot of cows, just around the bend from  craggy Mount Kosciusko. Other settlers followed, and watched their cows grow fat on the land after each lean, cold winter. 

      Then, around 1944, the government came along and decided to use the mountain, Australia's highest, for a hydroelectric plan. The whole million-acre  region was declared a national park and all grazing stopped as work got under way. Dozens of families who had followed the Williamsons abandoned their pastures but let their dwellings stand, turning the area into a virtual museum of early Australian settlement. Today, the enormous system of reservoirs and dams that makes up the Snowy Mountains Hydroelectric Scheme runs through the hills and fields dominated by these old dwelling places, where people from Sydney and Melbourne come to spend time in the unforgiving landscape of their ancestors.
